I love both. As range toys I think a 1911 that's well set up--and this will require a gunsmith to do hand fitting of the trigger, sear, hammer, and disconnector--with a really good trigger, like four pounds crisp with almost all the takeup, overtravel, and reset travel dialed out of it--is like almost nothing else on the range except maybe a good quality revolver being thumb-cocked to fire single action. They are amazing range toys when you get one that runs well. Compared to modern designs they're finicky about ammo, though part of the problem is that it's expensive to make a big leaf spring extractor that meets pre-WWI milspec nowadays and everybody's just putting in a cast part that may not hold the right tension. The BHP can have a trigger almost as nice and with a double column magazine it may be a bit more practical for duty or defense, maybe, though 13 round mags in a gun so much bigger and heavier than a Glock 19 isn't very competitive nowadays either.

Polymer gun triggers are always mushy and squishy. My theory is that you can feel the frame flexing a bit as you take up pressure and exert force on it. If you learned to shoot on a metal gun with a halfway decent trigger, even the best aftermarket trigger in a Glock, even the "tactical match" trigger in a USP, will be off-putting, at least in a "range toy" context.

I will probably regret it horribly but I just got a Taurus TX22, a striker fired polymer framed .22 pistol. I picked out one that didn't have a lot of chatter marks in the rifling or burrs on the crown, one where the barrel didn't rattle too much inside the slide. Maybe it'll run. It points and balances about like a Smith M&P or maybe an HK P30, and it's got that kind-of-squishy polymer gun trigger. It feels a lot like an M&P trigger, and an M&P in .40 is the bedside gun here. Practice with guns with mediocre triggers forces me to up my game on trigger control and will help me shoot the nice guns better.
